 Colson Whitehead), rap music (e.g., Jay Z), images of black homelessness, and figurations of political activism (civil rights activist Bayard Rustin, #BlackLivesMatter in Ferguson).  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2019: Backlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aRacism in literature. 0aViolence in literature. 4aAfrican American Literature. 4aAmerica. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aBlack Culture. 4aCapital. 4aCultural Sociology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEstablished-Outsider Relationships. 4aField. 4aHabitus. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aNorbert Elias. 4aPierre Bourdieu. 4aPolitical Activism. 4aPower Asymmetries. 4aPower Imbalances. 4aPower Relations. 4aRacism. 4aRap Music. 4aSocial Relations. 4aSociological Theory. 4aSociology of Literature. 4aSymbolic Violence. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican American Literature.  aAmerica.  aAmerican Studies.  aBlack Culture.  aCapital.  aCultural Sociology.  aCultural Studies.  aEstablished-Outsider Relationships.  aField.  aHabitus.  aLiterary Studies.  aNorbert Elias.  aPierre Bourdieu.  aPolitical Activism.  aPower Asymmetries.  aPower Imbalances.  aPower Relations.  aRacism.  aRap Music.  aSocial Relations.  aSociological Theory.  aSociology of Literature.  aSymbolic Violence.1 aBuschendorf, Christa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators